sec.p:
The alignment anchor sequences and divergent sequences/gaps of each read are analyzed by Python scripts to detect reads containing novel adjacencies (reads possessing split-read or hard-clipped alignments) and subsequently characterize their SV class. A novel adjacency is defined as two adjacent genomic coordinates in a sample genome that are not found to be adjacent in the reference genome. A novel adjacency is represented as two genomic coordinates in the reference genome, each known as a breakend. We use an algorithm of conditional control statements for novel adjacency detection and SV characterization, described in Additional file 1: Fig. S1. Any read that is found to possess a novel adjacency is labeled as an SV-associated read, otherwise, labeled as a normal read. Next, the read depth was calculated at each breakend for SV-associated reads and normal reads separately. This gives us the number of breakend-supporting reads B and breakend-opposing reads O at each breakend. Due to repetitive sequences in the genome, artificial breakends with unusually high B may be falsely detected. In order to filter out these untrue breakends, we define the upper limit of B as U, where breakends with B > U are considered outliers and removed. U is calculated by
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
